    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-10-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-10-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="268"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d268">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Roosevelt Papers: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_CWS1" type="from"
                            >Churchill</persName> to President <persName corresp="#p_RFD1" type="to"
                            >Roosevelt</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d268fn1">Sent by the United States Military Attaché, London,
                        via Army channels. For other excerpts from this telegram, see <hi
                            rend="italic">ante</hi>. <ref target="#pg_10">pp. 10</ref>, <ref
                            target="#pg_159">159</ref>–<ref target="#pg_160">160</ref>, <ref
                            target="#pg_206">206</ref>, <ref target="#pg_328">328</ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Excerpts]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-10-22">22 October
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Prime Minister to President <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName>
                    Personal and Top Secret Number 801.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <p>Para 5. Major war criminals U. J. took an unexpectedly ultra-respectable line.
                    There must be no executions without trial otherwise the world would say we were
                    afraid to try them. I pointed out the difficulties in International law but he
                    replied if there were no trials there must be no death sentences, but only
                    life-long confinements. In face of this view from this quarter I do not wish to
                    press the memo I gave you which you said you would have examined by the State
                    Department. Kindly therefore treat it as withdrawn.<note n="2" xml:id="d268fn2">
                        <p>In reply (No. 632, dated October 22, 1944) <persName corresp="#p_RFD1"
                                >Roosevelt</persName> commented: “Your statement of the present
                            attitude of U. J. towards war criminals, the future of Germany, and
                            Montreux convention is most interesting. We should discuss these matters
                            together with our Pacific war effort at the forthcoming three party
                            meeting.”</p>
                        <p>The text of <persName corresp="#p_CWS1">Churchill</persName>’s paragraph
                            5 was communicated to the Department of State (740.00116 <gloss
                                target="#t_EW1">EW</gloss>/10–2544).</p>
                    </note>
                </p>
